    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a clear emphasis on high-ceiling matchups against weaker arms, anchored by **Trea Turner** (81.27) and **Kyle Schwarber** (79.42). Both benefit significantly from a favorable clash against Martin P\u00e9rez, whose high xERA (4.78) provides a launching pad for our primary power-speed threats. **Trea Turner** remains our premier play, leveraging a stellar 19% SP skill advantage and the prime lead-off spot. Meanwhile, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (73.14) and **Hyeseong Kim** (70.16) present as our most efficient starts outside the primary power core; **Pete Crow-Armstrong** specifically benefits from a 14% dynamic platoon boost, making him a sneaky source of SB efficiency despite his lower spot in the order. We are leaning heavily into the platoon edges today, with **Yordan Alvarez** (64.91) rounding out the top-tier of our lineup, maintaining strong plate discipline metrics even against a middling arm.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision was the exclusion of **Josh Smith** (38.06). While he shows promise, his matchup against the elite Logan Gilbert\u2014who boasts a formidable 2.86 xERA\u2014pushed his score well below our organizational floor of 40.0. We are electing to sacrifice his utility for the higher floor provided by **Caleb Durbin** (51.20) and **Chase Meidroth** (50.74), who remain in the lineup due to more favorable situational factors despite the scarcity of the MI position. We continue to monitor **Christian Yelich** on the IL and wait for the return of **Colt Keith** and **Zac Veen**, whose absence leaves us thin, but the current configuration of **Gary Sanchez**, **Dillon Dingler**, **Kazuma Okamoto**, **Junior Caminero**, **Carson Benge**, and **Victor Scott II** offers the best balance of speed and raw production to compete in the 5x5 Roto format today. **Lars Nootbaar**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, and **Luis Pena** remain on the periphery, ready to rotate in should the bench depth requirements evolve during the homestand.",
